# Section 2 — Failed Attempt

## Attempt 1: Direct WebSocket command handling

Initially, the WebSocket response was directly read after sending a command.

Problem:

Chrome sends multiple event messages:

```
Page.frameStartedLoading
Page.frameNavigated
Runtime.executionContextCreated
Command Response
```

Because events do not contain an `id`, the program sometimes tried to parse them as command responses.

### Improvement:

Implemented request ID matching:

```cpp
request["id"] = currentID;
```

and verified:

```cpp
response["id"] == currentID
```

before accepting the response.

---

## Attempt 2: Using fixed sleep delay for page loading

A fixed delay approach was considered for waiting until the page was loaded.

Problem:

* Fast pages waste time.
* Slow JavaScript pages may not finish rendering.

### Learning:

A proper CDP event-based approach using:

```
Page.loadEventFired
```

is more reliable and will be implemented through better event handling.

---

## Attempt 3: Simple href searching in HTML Parser

Initially, searching directly for `"href"` caused incorrect matches in some cases.

Problem:

A normal string search could match:

```html
data-href=""
```

or other attributes containing similar text.

### Improvement:

Implemented attribute validation:

* Checked characters before `href`.
* Ensured `href` appears as an actual HTML attribute.
* Extracted only valid quoted URLs.

---

## Attempt 4: Using direct storage of URLs without duplicate handling

Problem:

The crawler could discover the same URL multiple times from different pages.

Example:

```
Page A
 |
 |---- https://example.com


Page B
 |
 |---- https://example.com
```

Without duplicate checking, the URL would repeatedly enter the frontier.

### Improvement:

Designed Seen Storage using the custom Set implementation.

